\section{Introduction}
\textit{Linux Virtual Server (LVS)} is one of the most efficient
traffic balancing server. In environments containing hundreds (if not thousands)
services plugged to \textit{LVS} it's becoming a challenge to
test services and make the right decision about plugging the server in or out.
Another problem about scalability in this matter is the lack of testing applications
especially for \textit{LVS}, where there are many servers plugged in and test 
frequency should not be longer than few seconds. That requirement reduces
list of usable applications, because they have to be based on multiplexed IO
(select/poll/epoll). So far the only application satisfying this requirements
was \textit{keepalived}. Because of it's bugs and lack of some functionalities
in \textit{keepalived} we decided to write a new service tester from scratch.
We called it \textit{SureAliveD}, because we wanted to make \underline{sure}
that services plugged to \textit{LVS} are working.

