\subsection{\textbf{SureAliveD} characteristics}
These are the main \textbf{surealived} tester features:
\begin{itemize}
\item based on epoll
\item flexible XML configuration (parsed by module)
\item service testers are in fact dynamically loaded modules
  (DSO - Dynamic Shared Object) -- it allows us to easily
  implement and add new service testers.
\item currently implemented testing modules are TCP protocol, HTTP,
  DNS, exec (executing external tester) and no-test (always treat server
  as available)
\item built-in transparent SSL support (just set SSL=''1'' attribute
  in tester configuration)
\item writes connection statistics for each server
  (time of connection and answer time)
\item two additional servers state table -- first holds info
  about servers that failed the test, and second keeps temporary
  configuration which overrides configuration from XML (server state
  and weight), those states are honoured after restart
\item on start configuration for \textbf{ipvssync} is saved
  and synchronization with \textit{IPVS} table is forced.
\item communication with \textbf{ipvssync} takes place via full
  synchronization file (written every 60 seconds) and via differential 
  configuration (written after every change)
\item tests start is spread in time (1 sec.), which reduces CPU load
  in case of simultaneous tests start for hundreds of reals
\item possibility to check configuration syntax (-t parameter)
\item application restart is not a problem
\item \textbf{surealived} can work just as service tester without
  synchronizing with \textit{IPVS}
\item opens a management port (1337 by default), allowing us
  to make some actions without application restart
\end{itemize}

